column1: Will a member of the Likud Party be the first person invited to form a government after the next Israeli general election?
column5: ['Yes, Benjamin Netanyahu', 'Yes, someone other than Benjamin Netanyahu', 'No']
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
All depends on turnout...

The electorate seems fatigued with Netanyahu. I would have thought the annexation announcement would have put him over the top - and it has not. Reports are out that his internal polling puts him behind - this is perhaps an effort to cajole supporters to come out - though if you have to resort to such as this - are these voters "supporters"?
This forecast is actually hard, as there are a lot of possible wildcards that can make the calculation of probabilities quite unreliable.
https://www.timesofisrael.com/4th-poll-shows-extremist-otzma-yehudit-in-knesset-blue-and-white-ahead-of-likud/
Benny Gantz.
a leader who always comes out of fights, conflicts and 'other somethings by gaining strength. I don't know if this will happen from the other. ^..^ .
Time update on the data.

Netanyahu represents an interesting but stable status quo for Israel at a time when Trump administration is leaning more towards giving the state all it wants. His recent move to annex areas of the heights plays well to hard liners and should be enough to swing it for him by pulling support away from hard line faction.

Likud and Netanyahu have scored a lot of points during Trump's office so far. Eyes are off The Palestinians and Israel is feeling less 'heat' with Netanyahu in charge. Israelis feel comfortable with him and are unlikely to want change.
Hedging my bets!
Israel is in thrall to Netanyahu. He will win if he runs. If not, his party seems to have a better chance than any other to hold a plurality and therefore to have the first opportunity.
There has been some security incidents recent and Netanyahu is a proven leader.
Israel is trending toward change.
With three cases being heard no telling what will happen.
They seem to be on a big push for votes.
I visited Israel this spring. There is a lot of opposition to Likud, and for those in Likud, Netanyahu is not is favor. I do not think the opposition can yet unseat Likud.
Purely on gut feeling: I'm miserably underinformed on Israeli politics - mea culpa!
I believe fear of the unknown will benefit a known entity.
Both Likud and Netanyahu look strong but anything can happen in an election. If Likud won, you would have to imagine that Netanyahu got hit by a truck not to get asked to lead a government

Opposition and government are both within margin of error on polls. Hard to pick a clear winner based on this. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_September_2019_Israeli_legislative_election

Netanyahu has been the great survivor of Israeli politics. I do think, between the corruption issues and failing to form a government the first time, that he going to lose both the election and control of the party but I've been wrong about him before. The fact that Likud doesn't seem to want this election tells me they don't think they will win it but I'm not counting them out.
The only party's so far to have led Isreal are Mapai/Labour, Likud and the now defunct Kadima.
Support for Likud is crumbling.
When it comes time to step into the voting booth the voters of Israel will give Netanyahu enough votes to be first to try and form the next government.

The corruption scandals lie heavy on Netanyahu, and the polls are heavily against him. Another member of Likud could have formed a government, but was blocked by Netanyahu. By the time he's finished I think Likuds chances of government are as well. Having said that he IS undermining Israel as we know it, and hence I think some sort violation of the Constitution is possible and so I only say 75% against

BNY is in deep trouble on both sides. He was largely dependent on gaining control after winning election but now that he could not form government, his support is dwindling gradually and his own supporters are having second thought. This can result in either losing election, which is highly likely. And even if party wins, Likud party is unlikely to project him as leader.
